<section id="what-comes-next" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Next Five Years Actually Look Like</h2>
  <p>First commercial regulatory approvals for mRNA cancer vaccines are anticipated between late 2026 and 2029, with melanoma and NSCLC as the leading candidates. The global market is projected to exceed $5–7 billion by 2030. Fifty-six percent of pharma and biotech executives identify mRNA as the most innovative current therapy in the industry; 93% agree that large pharmaceutical companies are making significant investments in it. The commercial infrastructure is being built.</p>
  <p>The autoimmune timeline is longer. No mRNA tolerizing vaccine has yet reached late-stage human trials. The preclinical data is compelling — the BioNTech <em>Science</em> paper, the Elsevier <em>Molecular Therapy</em> review, the Johns Hopkins work on Treg expansion — but compelling preclinical data has a long and undistinguished history of failing to translate. The first human tolerizing vaccine trials will likely read out within the next three to five years. Whether they confirm the mouse data is genuinely unknown.</p>
  <p>The manufacturing bottleneck will not resolve itself. The reduction from nine weeks to four weeks in personalized vaccine production is real progress. It is not sufficient progress for a therapy that needs to reach patients in the window between surgery and recurrence. Further compression requires investment in automated synthesis platforms, AI-guided quality control, and distributed manufacturing infrastructure — all of which require sustained public and private funding. One of those funding streams just lost $500 million.</p>
  <p>The equity problem has no current solution. A therapy that costs $100,000–$300,000 per patient, requires cold-chain logistics, and is manufactured in a handful of specialized facilities is not a global health intervention. It is a premium oncology product for patients in high-income countries with comprehensive insurance coverage. That may change as manufacturing scales and competition increases. It may not. The history of precision oncology — targeted therapies, checkpoint inhibitors — does not provide much basis for optimism about spontaneous price reduction.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-reckoning" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Reckoning</h2>
  <p>The five-year melanoma data is real. The pancreatic T cells circulating nearly four years after vaccination are real. The MD Anderson survival signal is real. The BioNTech tolerizing vaccine data is real. The molecular logic connecting all of it — a single platform running in opposite directions to either activate or suppress the immune system with antigen-specific precision — is real, and it is genuinely without precedent in the history of immunotherapy.</p>
  <p>And a federal government just cut half a billion dollars from the programs developing it. The National Cancer Institute lost 31% of its budget in the first quarter of 2025. The same public that would benefit from these treatments is being told, on platforms that reach hundreds of millions of people, that mRNA vaccines cause "turbo cancer" — a claim that is not only false but is the precise inverse of what the best available evidence shows.</p>
  <p>The science does not require triumphalism. It requires time, funding, rigorous Phase 3 trials, manufacturing investment, and a public health infrastructure capable of delivering a cold-chain-dependent personalized therapy to patients who need it. Three of those five requirements are currently being actively undermined.</p>
  <p>The uncomfortable question is not rhetorical. If this platform delivers what the early data suggests — if the Phase 3 melanoma approval comes through, if the pancreatic cancer signal holds in randomized trials, if the tolerizing vaccine reduces MS relapses without systemic immunosuppression — and we defunded the research infrastructure that would have accelerated it, what do we call that decision?</p>
  <p>We call it a choice. Made with full information. In 2025.</p>
</section>

